## 1. Steady (runsteady.com)

The product Powell named in the prompt. Positions itself as a "lightweight teamwork OS" rather than just a standup bot.

### Features

- Smart Check-ins — async daily check-ins delivered via Slack, Teams, web, or email; pull commits, PRs, Jira/Linear tickets in automatically so devs don't have to type "worked on PROJ-1234"
- Echoes — AI agents that you prompt in natural language ("summarize all PRs merged in the last 2 weeks") and that deliver scheduled or on-demand reports via DM
- Goal Stories — weekly/biweekly cross-team narrative updates with AI-drafted templates that summarize underlying tool activity
- Blocker alerts — managers get pinged the moment someone reports a blocker in their check-in
- Multi-team support — one person can check in to multiple teams at once with unified views
- Insights — analytics on participation rates, blocker frequency, intentions met, cross-correlated with GitHub/Jira activity
- 20+ integrations — GitHub, GitLab, Jira, Linear, Asana, Trello, Shortcut, Monday, Confluence, Zoom, Google Calendar, Slack, Teams
- MCP support — works with Claude, ChatGPT, and other MCP-aware assistants

### Pros

- Deepest integration story of any tool reviewed; activity flows in automatically rather than being manually pasted
- The Echoes AI-agent pattern is genuinely novel and is the closest thing to "AI in the team coordination loop"
- Multi-team support handles real-world org structures where people sit across teams
- Replaces standups, sprint planning prep, and 1:1 context assembly with one tool, so it's not just a standup bot
- Distinguishes between "personalized DMs" (private) vs "feed" (shared), reducing notification noise

### Cons

- Heavy. Lots of moving parts (Smart Check-ins, Goal Stories, Echoes, Insights) with a learning curve
- AI agents track human activity, but there's no first-class concept of an AI agent itself being a teammate that needs check-ins
- Built for medium-to-large orgs; overkill for a small team
- Closed source, paid SaaS; not transparent about what the AI sees

