## 2. Geekbot

The most established and widely-used async standup bot. Slack/Teams-only. Used by GitLab, Netflix, Shopify, Zapier, and 200,000+ users.

### Features

- DMs each team member on a configurable schedule with customizable questions; posts answers to a shared channel
- Templates for daily standup, retrospective, weekly review, mood/wellbeing, Friday Kudos
- Threaded follow-up so side discussions don't extend the standup for everyone
- Searchable history and dashboard
- Timezone handling per-user (you can set "DM me when I come online after X time")
- Polls and surveys
- Friday Kudos for peer recognition
- Free for up to 10 users; ~$2.50/user/month after

### Pros

- Dead simple to set up (5 minutes per user reviews)
- Lives entirely in Slack, so no extra app to log into
- Great timezone handling, repeatedly called out in reviews
- Customizable questions let you adapt it to any cadence (daily, weekly, retro, etc.)
- Built-in mood/wellbeing template directly addresses the "are we feeling bad?" question in the SE SitRep prompt
- Friday Kudos covers peer recognition without a separate tool

### Cons

- Pure question-based. If devs write "same as yesterday" or "fixed bugs, fixing more bugs," the data is useless. Reviews and articles repeatedly call this out
- No integration that pulls GitHub/Jira activity in automatically; you have to paste links yourself
- No first-class blocker tracking or escalation, just whatever the user types
- Standalone Slack bot only; no concept of cross-team coordination or rollups
- Limited template library compared to Standuply (per Capterra reviews)
- No AI agent tracking
- Initial setup of the dashboard outside Slack is reportedly clunky

