## 3. Range

Web-first async check-in tool with a heavy team-culture focus.

### Features

- Daily check-ins answering "yesterday / today / how I'm feeling"
- Red/yellow/green mood indicator plus 1800+ emoji options for daily mood expression
- 350+ icebreaker questions to rotate through for team-building
- Flags — items raised on a check-in to "bring up as a group" so synchronous standup time is spent only on flagged items
- Team Dashboard tracking team mood over time, intended for managers to spot burnout early
- Hashtags to track work streams
- 75+ tool integrations (GitHub, GitLab, Asana, Trello, Jira, Google Drive, Calendar)
- Slack and Microsoft Teams integration; Range can be added as a tab to a Teams meeting invite to surface moods/flags before the meeting

### Pros

- Best-in-class mood and wellbeing UX. The red/yellow/green system is simple, low-friction, and directly maps to the "are we feeling bad?" prompt question
- Flags are a smart UX pattern: instead of every standup item being equal, you mark what needs discussion. Reviewers report 50% reduction in standup length
- Strong integration list; pulls work items into check-ins like Steady does
- Designed for the human/cultural side of standups, not just status reporting

### Cons

- Lighter on analytics than Steady; no AI agent layer for synthesis
- No native goals or OKR depth (Steady, Jell are stronger here)
- No AI agent tracking
- Some users dislike having a separate web app on top of Slack
- Authentication quirks on Microsoft Teams (no email-link sign-in)

