## 5. Standuply

Slack/Teams agile-ceremony bot, the most Scrum-focused tool in the space.

### Features

- Async standups, retros, planning poker, and backlog grooming
- Text, voice, OR video responses (the only major tool that supports voice notes for standup answers)
- Jira and Trello deep integration; pulls ticket data into responses on the free tier
- Recurring polls, Q&A knowledge base, mood surveys
- Free for up to 3 users; Team plan ~$2-3.50/user/month, flat $199/month for up to 200 users, Business at $299/month for retros and planning poker

### Pros

- Only tool that automates planning poker and full retros end-to-end, valuable for Scrum teams
- Voice/video responses are a real UX win for devs who hate typing standups
- Free tier includes Jira integration, which is unusual
- Deep Q&A bot routes unanswered questions to the right person
- Strong if your whole team lives in Slack and runs textbook Scrum

### Cons

- Mainly only useful if you do textbook Scrum; for non-Scrum teams much of the surface area is wasted
- Jira-centric; less compelling if your team uses Linear or GitHub Projects
- Free tier is only 3 users
- No AI agent tracking
- Reviews note the setup curve is steeper than Geekbot

