## Analysis: where the gap is

Three observations from this matrix:

**1. The "feeling bad / cover for me" axis is partially solved but never well.**
Range nailed the UX of mood (red/yellow/green plus emoji), and DailyBot does AI-driven sentiment, but no tool turns "I'm feeling burnt out" or "I'm sick" into an actionable "who can cover this?" workflow. The prompt asks "do we need someone to cover for us?" and no current tool answers that question; they only surface the signal and leave the decision to a human manager. A coverage-suggestion feature based on declared availability, current load, and skills overlap would be a real differentiator.

**2. "When can we all meet?" is barely addressed.**
Every tool in this space integrates with Google Calendar to pull availability, but none of them do the actual scheduling problem (finding a time that works for everyone) inside the standup tool. That's left to Calendly, When2Meet, or the calendar itself. Folding meeting-finding directly into the team status feed would close a real gap, especially for small teams that don't want to context-switch to a scheduling tool.

**3. AI agents are completely untracked. This is our differentiator.**
Every tool in the space assumes a team is humans only. But teams in 2026 increasingly include AI coding agents (Claude Code, Cursor agents, Codex, Gemini CLI) doing meaningful work, sometimes 10-20 parallel agents per developer per Builder.io's writeup. None of Steady, Geekbot, Range, DailyBot, or Standuply have a concept of "what did the AI agents do yesterday, what are they working on today, are any of them stuck waiting for human review." This is exactly what Powell flagged in the prompt and exactly where SE SitRep can stake out new ground. Concretely this would mean: an agent run shows up in the team feed with what it touched, what PRs it opened, what it's blocked on (e.g. waiting for review or hitting a rate limit), and the human teammate it's "assigned to" gets pinged just like a human teammate would be on a blocker.

**4. There is no open-source, lightweight option for small teams.**
Every serious tool is paid SaaS. Slack Workflow Builder is the only free baseline, and it's barely usable. A small team running a class project, a hackathon, or a 4-person startup has no good free option. Since our project is web-first and free by default, we land naturally in this gap.

## Recommendations for our feature scope

Given the above, the SE SitRep MVP should prioritize, in this order:

1. Async check-ins with the standard 3 questions (yesterday / today / blockers), with a fourth question for mood (red/yellow/green like Range)
2. A team feed that shows everyone's check-in for the day plus who hasn't checked in yet
3. Blocker surfacing: when someone reports a blocker, it gets pinned and the team lead gets notified
4. AI agent check-ins: a way to register an AI agent as a teammate and have it post its own check-in (manual entry initially, with a clear path to GitHub/CLI integration later)
5. "Who can cover" suggestion when someone marks themselves out or red-status
6. Meeting time suggestion based on declared availability windows

Items 4 and 5 are the differentiators. Items 1-3 are table stakes; if we don't do them, we're not in the category.

